Magic Story Update:
Merfolk centered! 
Kopala narrates. Shapers were the original lords of the land, the other factions have forgotten their origins, but the shapers haven’t. 9 Shapers for the nine Tributaries around Ixalan. Shapers take the name of the river they are “guided” by. Tishana is Kopala’s Mentor, and she is the oldest of the Shapers. Kumena and Tishana are the most powerful of the Shapers. 
Stand Off between Kumena and Tishana. Kumena says relocate Orazca, and secure the Immortal Sun.
“The Immortal Sun has brought ruin once, and we barely survived.”
Kopala sides with Tishana, and Kumena revolts. Seeking the Immortal Sun himself.
Kumena and Tishana meet, Orazca == Atlantis, (“raise a city once.”), Kumena strikes and knocks out Tishana. 

Also talk of a “Last Guardian” who entrusted the River Heralds to protect the Immortal Sun, but not with it. 
Only pirates searching for the Immortal Sun are Vraska and Angrath’s Group.

Hrm...that’s actually tough. Asceticism is a removal target, but no one will waste spot removal on the bestiary. The bestiary also replicates what Reki does, though naturally in a more limited and less efficient manner, so it’s more on theme.
I had originally cut a land but in goldfishing it feels off. That might entirely be mental, but it just feels not right, and it's gonna bug me so I'm gonna try and get back to 36 lands.
In mono-green? That seems a little on the high side, though it probably depends on how many utility lands you run.
9 utility non-forests. Ancient Tomb, Homeward Path, Nykthos, Reliquary Tower, Scavenger Grounds, Scrying Sheets, Strip Mine, Terrain Generator, Untaidake
Hrm. That’s pretty high so I understand wanting the keep the forest count high. I assume you’re running snow forests, given the Sheets.
Yeah, for Lens and Into the North

I could pull Sheets for a basic easily, I so rarely use it, but I've also never had it be a problem. Honestly a lot of it is probably me mentally thinking it feels off. Statistically speaking 1 less land is going ot make a difference in your first ten turns a rounding error amount of times.
it's that curve that you gotta be worried about
People overestimate the value of a curve in EDH
That's not to say you should run all 8 drops and have no options in the first three turns, but the variance on 100 cards makes hitting your curve way harder than in 60
Sol Ring, Tomb and Untaidake in the opening hand give a turn 2 Reki and Rampant Growth, Into the North and Nature's Lore on turns I don't, so there's enough early turn stuff

It's also tricky to do much with given I'm restricted to mono-green legends. It's been slowly improving. Hope of Ghirapur, Oviya Pashiri, Rishkar, Rhonas and Sevala are all from the last year and are 3 or less, so just by virtue of getting more options I've been able to creep it downward.
Though I've found I'd rather not play 1 drops even when I can. I'd rather take a few shots to the face on turn 2 or 3 to play them after Reki and draw a card.

Well, while I agree that curve is not the be all end all, and in fact is only REALLY important in beat down decks. However, it is curve the ultimately determines your mana base, when you need to hit what lands is all a curve consideration
